    weekTitle: "A Covenant That Lasts",
    title: "My Beloved Is Mine, and I Am His",
    ref: "Song of Solomon 2:16",
    scripture: "My beloved is mine, and I am his: he feedeth among the lilies.",
    walk: `Friend, today's verse from the Song of Solomon expresses the mutual belonging of love, the sweet possession of husband and wife: *My beloved is mine, and I am his.* In marriage, friend, two belong to each other; let us walk in this sweet belonging today.

See the mutual belonging, friend: *My beloved is mine, and I am his.* Here is the language of love, friend, the sweet belonging of husband and wife: my beloved is mine, and I am his. There is a mutual possession in marriage, friend, a belonging to one another: my beloved is mine, says the wife; and I am his. Each belongs to the other, friend; each is the other's; there is a sweet, mutual possession in marriage. This is not a possession of ownership, friend, as a master owns a slave; it is the sweet belonging of love, each giving themselves to the other, each belonging to the other in love.

What a sweet truth this is for marriage, friend. In marriage, friend, you belong to your spouse, and your spouse belongs to you; my beloved is mine, and I am his. There is a security in this belonging, friend, a sweetness, a comfort: to know that you are your spouse's, and your spouse is yours; that you belong to one another, are given to one another, are each other's. In a world where so much is uncertain, friend, here is something settled and sure: that you are not alone, not unclaimed, not adrift; you are your beloved's, and your beloved is yours. This mutual belonging, friend, is one of the great sweetnesses of marriage: to be wholly another's, and to have another wholly your own, in the bond of love.

And notice, friend, that this belonging is exclusive. My beloved is mine, friend, and I am his; not another's, but his; not shared with others, but belonging to one another alone. This is the exclusive belonging of marriage, friend, the faithfulness that gives oneself to one's spouse alone, and receives one's spouse as one's own alone. This exclusive belonging, friend, is the heart of faithfulness in marriage: that we belong to our spouse alone, and our spouse to us alone, with no other sharing in that belonging.

So let us treasure this sweet and exclusive belonging in our marriages, friend. Let us know the sweetness, friend, of belonging to our spouse and having our spouse belong to us: my beloved is mine, and I am his. Let us rest in the security of this belonging, friend, the comfort of being wholly another's and having another wholly our own. And let us guard the exclusiveness of this belonging, friend, the faithfulness that belongs to our spouse alone; for my beloved is mine, and I am his, not another's. Let us give ourselves wholly to our spouses, friend, and receive them as wholly our own; let us belong to one another, faithfully and exclusively, in the sweet bond of love. For this is one of the great gifts of marriage, friend: the sweet, secure, exclusive belonging of two who are each other's. My beloved is mine, friend, and I am his; let us treasure and guard this belonging, that our marriages may be marked by the sweetness and faithfulness of those who wholly belong to one another.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for the sweet belonging of marriage: that my beloved is mine, and I am his; that in marriage, two belong wholly to one another. Help me to treasure this belonging, Lord, the sweetness and security of being wholly my spouse's, and having my spouse wholly my own. Help me to rest in this belonging, Lord, in the comfort of being each other's. And help me to guard the exclusiveness of this belonging, Lord, the faithfulness that belongs to my spouse alone; to give myself wholly to my spouse, and to receive them as wholly my own, with no other sharing in that belonging. Let our marriage be marked, Lord, by the sweetness and faithfulness of those who wholly belong to one another. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, treasure your belonging. Tell or show your spouse, in some clear way, that you are wholly theirs and they are wholly yours — savoring and guarding the sweet, exclusive belonging of marriage.`,
