    walk: `Friend, we continue in the great love chapter, with a verse that shows the enduring, all-weathering nature of love, just what a lasting covenant needs: *Beareth all things, believeth all things, hopeth all things, endureth all things.* Love bears and endures all things, friend; let us walk in this today.

See first, friend: *Beareth all things.* Love bears all things, friend; it bears up under all, carries the burdens, endures the hardships, covers and protects. In marriage, friend, this means a love that bears all things: that carries the burdens of marriage, endures its hardships, covers and protects the spouse. A love that bears all things, friend, does not collapse under difficulty, but bears up, carries on, endures.

See next, friend: *believeth all things.* Love believes all things, friend; it is not suspicious or cynical, but believes the best, trusts, gives the benefit of the doubt. In marriage, friend, this means a love that believes the best of the spouse, that is not suspicious or cynical, that trusts and gives the benefit of the doubt. How much marriage needs this believing love, friend, that thinks the best rather than the worst of the spouse.

See next, friend: *hopeth all things.* Love hopes all things, friend; it is hopeful, not despairing; it hopes for good, looks for the best, does not give up hope. In marriage, friend, this means a love that hopes for the best, that does not give up on the spouse or the marriage, that keeps hoping even in hard times. A hopeful love, friend, does not despair of the marriage, but keeps hoping, looking for good, trusting God for the future.

And see finally, friend: *endureth all things.* Love endures all things, friend; it lasts, persists, holds out to the end, does not give up. In marriage, friend, this means a love that endures all things: that lasts through every trial, persists through every hardship, holds out to the end, does not give up. This is the enduring love a lasting covenant needs, friend: a love that endures all things, holding out to the very end.

So let us love our spouses with this enduring, all-weathering love, friend. Let us bear all things, friend, carrying the burdens, enduring the hardships, not collapsing under difficulty. Let us believe all things, friend, believing the best of our spouse, not suspicious or cynical. Let us hope all things, friend, hoping for the best, not giving up on our spouse or our marriage. And let us endure all things, friend, lasting through every trial, holding out to the very end. For this is the love that makes a covenant last, friend: a love that bears, believes, hopes, and endures all things. A marriage built on such love, friend, endures; for the love that bears and believes and hopes and endures all things does not give up, does not collapse, but lasts to the end. So let us build our marriages on this enduring love, friend; let us love our spouses with a love that bears all, believes all, hopes all, endures all; that our covenant may last, weathering all things, holding out to the very end. For love like this, friend, never fails.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for this picture of enduring, all-weathering love: that bears all things, believes all things, hopes all things, endures all things. Help me to love my spouse with such love, Lord. Help me to bear all things, carrying the burdens of marriage, enduring its hardships, not collapsing under difficulty. Help me to believe all things, believing the best of my spouse, not suspicious or cynical. Help me to hope all things, hoping for the best, not giving up on my spouse or my marriage. And help me to endure all things, Lord, lasting through every trial, holding out to the very end. Build our marriage on this enduring love, Lord, that bears and believes and hopes and endures all things, the love that never fails. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
